Scientific & Statistical Analysis: Clock Calibration, Transportability, and Recalibration
Question 1: Were the correct BioAge functions used for NHANES calibration?

Yes, the implementation is methodologically correct. Your R/train.R calls:

    BioAge::phenoage_nhanes(biomarkers) — trains a Gompertz proportional hazards model on NHANES III mortality data, projects to NHANES IV
    BioAge::kdm_nhanes(biomarkers) — Klemera-Doubal method training
    BioAge::hd_nhanes(biomarkers) — Homeostatic Dysregulation training

For each sub-clock (hepatic_lipid, hema_integrated, etc.), phenoage_nhanes() is called with the reduced biomarker panel. This is the canonical approach described in Kwon & Bheler (2021): the BioAge toolkit allows users to re-derive PhenoAge with different biomarker sets while preserving the Gompertz mortality framework.

One caveat: The sub-clocks use 2-5 biomarkers instead of Levine's original 9. The Gompertz mortality model's predictive accuracy degrades with fewer covariates, meaning the sub-clock "PhenoAge" values are noisier estimates. This is methodologically acceptable for exploratory organ-system profiling, but these sub-clocks should not be interpreted with the same confidence as the full PhenoAge.
Question 2: Were the correct formulas applied when transferring to your population?

Yes. Your run_clinical_lite.R calls BioAge::phenoage_calc(data, biomarkers, fit), which:

    Extracts coefficients from the $fit object trained on NHANES III
    Computes linear predictor: xb = Σ(βᵢ × Xᵢ) + intercept
    Calculates Gompertz mortality score: M = 1 - exp(m_n × exp(xb) / m_d)
    Inverts to PhenoAge: PhenoAge = BA_i + log(BA_n × log(1-M)) / BA_d

The coefficients, Gompertz parameters (m_n, m_d), and PhenoAge inversion constants (BA_i, BA_n, BA_d) are all taken from the NHANES-trained $fit object — no custom modifications. This is the standard deployment approach.
Question 3: The population offset problem

Your deep analysis output confirms exactly what the literature predicts. Your Argentine cohort shows systematic negative advancement across all clocks:
Clock	Mean Advancement	Interpretation
hema_integrated	-3.5 years	Patients appear 3.5y younger
micronutrient_methylation	-3.3 years	Patients appear 3.3y younger
hepatic_lipid	-0.4 years	Modest offset

This mirrors findings in the German NAKO cohort (n=173,925) where every single subgroup showed negative PhenoAgeAccel (mean = -6.1 years). It also appears in Chinese cohorts and UK Biobank applications.

Why does this happen? Three non-mutually-exclusive explanations:

    Population health differences: NHANES III (1988-1994) captured a US population with different metabolic profiles, dietary patterns, obesity rates, and comorbidity prevalence than a 2020s Argentine private lab cohort. A private lab population is inherently healthier (they have access to healthcare, they're being proactive about testing).

    Assay calibration differences: Laboratory instrumentation, reagent lots, and measurement standards differ between NHANES reference labs and Argentine clinical labs. Even small systematic differences in albumin, CRP, or creatinine measurements propagate through the Gompertz formula.

    Temporal drift: NHANES III was conducted in 1988-1994. Secular trends in biomarker distributions (declining cholesterol from statin use, changing CRP distributions) create a calibration mismatch with 2020s data.

Question 4: Is there a statistically valid way to re-center the clocks?

Yes. There are multiple approaches, ranked from most conservative to most aggressive:
Approach A: Residual-based recentering (what you already do, partially)

Your code residualizes advancement against age using NHANES-derived regression coefficients:

residual = advancement - (intercept_nhanes + slope_nhanes × age)
z_score = (residual - mean_nhanes) / sd_nhanes

The problem: You're using NHANES reference statistics (mean_nhanes, sd_nhanes) as the denominator. This preserves the population offset — an Argentine patient with perfectly average biomarkers for their age will get a negative Z-score because NHANES patients at that age had worse values.

The fix — study-population recentering:

# Regress PhenoAge on chronological age WITHIN your cohort
fit_local <- lm(PhenoAge ~ age, data = argentine_data)
PhenoAgeAccel_local <- residuals(fit_local)

# Standardize within cohort
z_local <- scale(PhenoAgeAccel_local)  # mean=0, SD=1

This is exactly what the ICU mortality study did: "The constant of the regression line represents the recalibrated constant of the relationship between PhenoAge and the chronological age in the current study context." It is the most commonly used approach in the literature and is statistically sound for within-cohort comparisons.

What this preserves: The ranking of patients — who is aging faster or slower relative to their peers in this population. The Gompertz coefficients still capture the same biological relationships (albumin is protective, CRP is deleterious, etc.).

What this loses: Absolute comparability with NHANES-referenced values. You can no longer say "this patient is 5 years biologically older than an average American of the same age."
Approach B: Dual-reference reporting

Report both:

    z_nhanes: Z-score against NHANES reference (for international comparability)
    z_local: Z-score against Argentine cohort (for clinical utility within your population)

This is the approach I'd recommend. It's transparent and lets the reader choose the reference frame.
Approach C: Age- and sex-stratified recentering

# Separate regression by sex
fit_F <- lm(PhenoAge ~ age, data = subset(df, sex == "F"))
fit_M <- lm(PhenoAge ~ age, data = subset(df, sex == "M"))

Your sex difference analysis showed Cohen's d = 0.43 for hepatic_lipid — a meaningful effect. The BioAge toolkit itself recommends sex-specific standardization: "KDM BA and PhenoAge values were standardized to have M=0, SD=1 separately for men and women."
